[Student "S"]
{South's 3NT rebid shows 6 \Ss headed by A K Q and nothing else. North is to play 7NT. East leads the \DQ.

Nice hand. You have 12 high card tricks and either a 3-2 \S split or a 3-3 \C split will land this Grand Slam. But even if neither suit splits nicely you can STILL make it if the same defender holds 4 cards in both suits; in that case you will squeeze for the thirteenth trick.

Win the \DK and (<b>IMPORTANT!</b>) test the \Cs first by playing \C A K Q. Darn. East discards a \D on the \CQ. 

Alright, so West holds the \C Guard. You still need to exercise caution.

Play your 4 \H winner's next. East follows suit while West follows twice, then discards 2 \Ds.  

Don't play \Ss yet!

Play your \DA. West must give up. 

If he throws the \CJ, you win. But if he throws a \S you also win. This is what is called a Win-Win bridge play.}
[Play "W"]DQ

